{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The conversation history passed to the LLM is trimmed to the most recent 10 messages when the full history exceeds the context window.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"The risk is at the handoff between history selection and LLM request construction (multi-module wiring), not model quality. A unit test of trimming logic alone can miss payload-assembly bugs. Higher levels were considered and rejected: no behavior text requires real HTTP/subprocess/OS, and correctness does not depend on real LLM output content.","test_description":"Run the chatbot service with real in-process modules and a stub LLM transport that records request payloads; submit a history >10 messages and assert the outbound LLM request contains exactly the latest 10 messages in order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated response addresses the customer's question rather than producing a generic or off-topic reply.","required_reality_check_level":"Agentic","justification":"This is output-quality/relevance validation, which depends on real model judgment. Deterministic mocks would hide off-topic/generic failures. Workflow was considered and rejected: behavior text asks for single-response relevance, not cross-step consistency across multiple model decisions.","test_description":"Use real LLM calls on a labeled set of customer questions and score whether responses are on-topic and question-answering (human rubric or model-graded with adjudication); fail if relevance falls below threshold.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.86,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration.","required_reality_check_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on tone judgment quality from a real model (too formal vs acceptable), so mocks can pass while real behavior fails. Workflow was considered and rejected: the behavior requires correct identification plus trigger, but does not require validating multi-step semantic consistency across several model outputs.","test_description":"With real LLM-based tone check enabled, feed responses known to be overly formal for casual-tier users and verify the system flags them and initiates a regeneration attempt; include borderline negatives to measure false triggers.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.2}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to the database with correct timestamps.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"The behavior explicitly requires proving an externally visible side effect via round-trip persistence/readback of the complete exchange and timestamps. Unit-only confidence is false here because write-path success must be validated at boundary level. Integration was considered but rejected because the behavior text requires full persisted exchange visibility (including regenerations and timestamp correctness) as an externally observable outcome.","test_description":"Execute an end-to-end chat turn (including a forced regeneration path), then read back stored records through the real persistence boundary and assert all entries exist, are linked correctly, and timestamps are correct/ordered.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.33,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — the customer never sees the rejected draft.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"This is an externally visible guarantee at the customer boundary (no leaked rejected draft), so round-trip observation at the serving interface is required. Agentic/Workflow were considered but rejected because the behavior text conditions on trigger already happening; it tests visibility/replacement semantics, not model decision quality.","test_description":"Run the live request path where regeneration is triggered, observe the actual customer-facing response/stream, and assert only the regenerated response is emitted while the rejected draft is never returned to the client.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.5,"Agentic":0.24,"Workflow":0.05}}]}
